ce:section.ce:para:
Liposomes are amphiphilic nano-spherical particles composed of two phospholipid bilayers, and have been widely applied in drug delivery and clinic diagnosis [155]. Due to their ability to protect PSs from degrading and aggregating in the body fluid environment, adjustable and biocompatible liposomes are qualified as outstanding PSs' carriers [156]. For example, to achieve targeted aPDT and controllable PSs release, Mai et al. modified the surface cationization of liposomes and loaded Sinoporphyrin sodium (DVDMS, the PS) into liposomes [157]. The results showed that cationic liposomes tightly targeted and adhered to P. aeruginosa through electrostatic interaction and generated ROS locally under irradiation. Under 100 J/cm2 light, cationic liposomes (20 μg/mL) reduced a 2.0-log CFU in MDR
                        P. aeruginosa. Furthermore, the high loading efficacy and versatile modifiability endow liposomes-based nanoplatforms great potential in multi-functional antibacterial PDT [31]. In a study, Cui et al. designed a novel polymyxin B (PMB)-targeted liposomal photosensitizer, hematoporphyrin monomethyl ether (HMME) @Lipo-PMB, for precise and potent aPDT against burn infections induced by MDR Acinetobacter baumannii (A. baumannii) (Fig. 7
                        ) [158]. As a positively charged lipopeptide antibiotic, PMB could specifically bind to the negatively charged phosphate groups of lipid A in the A. baumannii membrane, compensating for the weak binding affinity of HMME for bacteria. As a result, HMME@Lipo-PMB-mediated aPDT exhibited excellent antimicrobial efficacy against MDR A. baumannii, resulting in a remarkable 8 log10 reduction in vitro, and completely cured MDR A. baumannii-induced burn infections in a mouse model. Furthermore, the study revealed the underlying mechanisms of aPDT on macrophage polarization. By inducing acute inflammation in the early stage and reducing chronic inflammation in the later stage, HMME@Lipo-PMB-aPDT promoted tissue repair, accelerated wound closure, and improved overall healing outcomes. In another study, Xiao et al. encapsulated ICG and rapamycin (an immunosuppressant) in liposomal nanoparticles, realizing antibacterial, anti-biofilm, and anti-inflammatory effects in implant-associated infection and periodontitis via liposome-based aPDT [159].
